Would you be willing to share details about your robot’s weight and drivetrain? We noticed that you were extremely fast compared to the rest of the field.

We had a blast playing with your team in Duluth and meeting the 930 crew!

Awesome robot this year, yet again!

I’m curious about the assembly and design of the turret setup for this robot.

image660×631 72.3 KB

I feel like I’m missing something, or parts aren’t in quite the right place. How is the bottom bearing retained? It looks like it’s just falling out of the plate, but there are holes nearby that might retain it.

It almost looks like this is a strain-wave/harmonic gearbox based on this piece, so I am assuming the sort of floating bearing is an eccentric one.

image668×590 39.1 KB

And then you have the hex shaft through the whole thing with the absolute encoder to track the position of the turret.

If I’m on the right track, this is a crazy cool turret design. Curious where you sourced the strain-wave components. If you in-house manufactured I would be absolutely blown away.

Our robot weighed in at about 113lbs at the championship (even lighter at Lake Superior). We also use L3 SDS mk4i swerve drives with Krakens and 16t motor pinions to increase the speed even more, which is likely the most significant factor in our speed.

We also had a lot of fun playing with you guys at Duluth

We have a similar drivetrain ratio setup but weighed 121.
During build season, we actually were running faster with our setup on our practice bot with Falcons (waiting for Kraken parts to come in). Speed was so important in this game.

I too was impressed with your turret and shot making abilities. It was definitely one of the most versatile shooters at the Midwest event.

Thanks for sharing.

On the real robot, the bearing is retained by a small 3D print mounted to the main support plate.

This is a strain-wave gearbox. The hex shaft was convenient as it allowed us to mount our encoder without the hassle of creating a separate gearbox like we did in 2020/21.

Overall, we were super happy with how seamlessly the harmonic gearbox was integrated into the design. The smaller profile was helpful for packaging and the gearbox itself worked with zero backlash and no noticeable wear the entirety of the season.

The strain-wave components were found and sourced by one of our mentors. When I see him next, I can get the details of where he got them.

Matt930:

The strain-wave components were found and sourced by one of our mentors. When I see him next, I can get the details of where he got them.

We found an ebay shop that seems to have a warehouse full of spare parts for industrial machinery. We just needed to 3dprint interfaces for the input and output shafts.

A couple of times this season the bore of the shooter gear directly driven by the motor rounded out. One time while just the kraken shaft profile was printed into the gear, and once at champs with the hex insert we have now. Other than that, all the gears and other 3d prints held up very well. Overall, we believe the ability to customize and reduce weight on our gears and pulleys outweigh the minor structural problems.

The intake bevel gears are 3d printed. We did not experience any issues with them.

So far, none of the onyx parts have had any noticeable wear, but I have no way of knowing if a PLA part with the same print settings would have failed or not, but I am confident the onyx parts would last longer due to the higher strength material. Since the parts were from a sponsor, we used around 25% infill on the onyx prints vs around 15% on the PLA ones. Both used 4 walls (which is honestly probably the most impactful setting for gears and pulleys since the biggest failure point is the bore). Most of the prints (onyx and PLA) used a gyroid infill, which is pretty standard.

Most of our prints this year consisted of gears, pulleys, and some camera mounts that didn’t take a ton of load. In 2023, we used a 3D print (PETG) combined with some aluminum plates to attach our arm to its rotation point, and we saw cracking partway through the season that we had to deal with for the rest of the season (although it never gave out). I think the strength difference in onyx vs standard filaments would be much more noticeable on load-bearing parts like an arm.

For 3D printed gears, you generally want the pitch around 10 DP. One of the biggest advantages to using 3d printed gears is the ability to customize the pitch.

This season, the large plates on the shooter were made to use gears with a 2:1 gear ratio. After the Wisconsin regional we changed the ratio to 1.5:1 by slightly increasing the DP of the printed gears without the need to change the plates.

Matt930:

you generally want the pitch around 10 DP

Another benefit of 10DP is that if you need to switch to aluminum/steel gears, you can buy 20DP at double the tooth count, and it will have the same pitch diameter.

So a 15T 10DP gear has the same pitch diameter of a 30T 20DP gear.
